So...  as this person has stopped leading and started spraying a lot of drivvel out into the internet.  I leave a rebuttal to his present state of mind Nov.  2024.  While this channel appears to do a lot of marketing of the computer programming profession and is VERY light on coding tips, tricks, and fundamentals I'd say he's a good cheerleader for the industry .  However, as his income and role at a company has diminished he's slacked off and gone into a sour grapes spiral of dissolutionment.  I believe this is unhealthy.  Human, but not healthy for an entire industry. My Credientals: 2 year ATA degree in electronic engineering, 4 year BS degree in Accounting.  And about 15 years combined paid experience .  So that's who I am.  Here's what I think:  Probably about 50% of the conclusions he draws are correct.  I can honestly attest to the boom and bust of tech jobs in the us.  That being said, what will help revitalize the companies, and create a modicum of job security  is as follows .  1.  When your not paid to work, spend time socializing and protesting in and for the place you live.  It sounds silly, but often management will estimate how hard they can push employees by the surrounding city vibe.  Short of unionizing, this is how semi-rational environments are created and sustained.  Remember, if your neighbor, and cohort doesn't know how each are being treated, managers will push people harder simply because there is no social pushback.  Think of it as a feedback loop.  Or part of an Asymmetrical information pool.  Businesses and managers have tons of knowledge and information us workers don't.  When we don't talk, they capitalize .  2.  He very well be accurate in the sentiment that large parts of the industry have reached saturation.  'Cesar wept, as there was no more land to conqure'.  But, in the tech game, the market of customers is literally always expanding or contracting.  If you have a secondary skillset, consider applying it.  If you don't have one, foster one.  Mix it in with some hobbies.  In the paid work world, jobs are created and destroyed for the glory of Rome(or wherever you live).  The people are ment to walk in and out of them according to the needs and wants of everyone surrounding you.  Seriously, this is true regardless of what country you live in, or the style of governance its under.  If somebody tells you to work for free by threat of physical harm, run, fight them and get away.  Cause their 'money' in that situation ain't worth a thing.  Literally worthless.  In conclusion: industries and companies grow and shrink.  It is cyclical inpart, because we and the planet we live on is also going through cycles.  Rather than victimizing ourselves, it's often healthier to refuse to not grow.  Even when the path changes radically for a while.  And when you get tired of working for Bosses, and we all will.  Maybe consider, just how to be the Boss of your own business.  It's literally easy to begin.  And a lifetimes pain in the bottom to complete!  Happy Trails, - O.G.

Dude, where did you go to college? During my Electrical Engineering degree studies, I was taught (not self-studied, actually taught by some full professors, who at times were pretty old) the following programming languages (in that order): FORTRAN (1st semester, introduction to computer science), Z80 assembler (2nd semester, introduction to computer organization), Pascal (4th semester, Data Structures), LISP (5th semester, Programming Languages), COBOL (6th semester, File Organizations and Systems Analysis), C (7th semester, Operating Systems), SQL (7th semester, Relational Databases), OCCAM (8th semester, Computer Systems Lab), PROLOG (8th semester, Expert Systems and Artificial Intelligence), and LOTOS (9th semester, Specification Languages for Formal Protocol Description) (in Greece, and in Europe in general, Technical Universities are 5-year programs). 5 years of study, 10 different (some times very exotic) languages! If you think why wasn't I taught Python and Java, it's because by the time I graduated, these languages didn't exist yet ğŸ™‚.  In the US, things are pretty similar: In UW-Madison (where I did my graduate studies), the freshmen CS majors had to take a mandatory course "Introduction to Computer Science" that basically taught them the C programming language. And so on... While I find your videos very intelligent and funny, I completely disagree with you on being an auto-didact for Computer Science: in the same way I don't think it would be good advice to study mathematics on your own and then proclaim yourself to be a mathematician, it's not good advice to study CS on your own. Better go to the best school that will accept you (and that you can afford), even if this is just the community college next door, than trying to learn some very complex concepts on your own, or through YouTube videos.

The first tip (ability to focus) is called "deep work" and there's the book with the same name. But you can easily search it up on youtube.  In summary, you sit and focus only only only on the thing you're supposed to be working on with 0 distractions. According to studies, distractions offput your full focus (the zone/flow state) by 5-20 minutes. So unless your house is on fire, checking email or reading that text someone send you is a big no-no.  You're supposed to sit and focus for 90 minutes max and then take a big break( 10-20 minutes is enough). But not for social media etc, but for a light exercise or talking with someone. Don't go for 90 minutes at first though start with 30 mins and if you feel fine after these 30 minutes, keep going. You're supposed to do only 3-4h of deep deep work per day. But it's like 3-10x results anyway. Any kind of focus and mindfulness exercise daily helps too.

My schooling was way back when on 386's, and 486's, (C++, Pascal, COBOL, and BASIC), and we didn't have multi-threaded computers back then, all the configurations we have today, with Dante's Inferno of toolchain hell, framework hell, ide/text editor hell, installation hell, help hell, etc...  and so many contradictions on the internet that say single-thread programming is better for this or that, then multi-threaded programming is good for this, but bad for that...  ...can I actually damage, my cpu, or gpu by using while loops without framerate capping?  One thing I discovered though, is there's nothing "standard" about C/C++ anymore, considering there's 20+ standards now for you to choose from.  I spend more time in frustration trying to get things to work, wondering what's been removed, and what's replaced what.  YT is no help, when it comes to searching knowledge, just trying searching for "C++ WinMain GUI tutorials", click on filters, "upload date", and you'll see what I have to go through, with only 3 to 8 results, if any at all.  Un-filtered, I get video's from 3 to 8 years ago.

I'm sorry but it does not sound like you have really any real life experience in software engineering and coding.  The overall picture is missing.  There are so many aspects to this and you need various skillsets and experiences to constitute a good project team and it varies over the lifecycle of the project and the maturity of the solution that you are seeking and/or working on.  Just being able to sit for hours in front of the computer is a social stigma and not an efficient reality.  The coding monkey is not a thing and if it is the company really needs to rethink and reinvent itself.   Of course being able to focus on the task at hand is crucial but often you need to stand up from the computer and let your mind wander so you can empower the left side of the brain and the subconscious mind to come up with fresh ideas and approaches. For example coders with ADHD can be invaluable if you allow them to flourish and they can come up with solutions and ides that a focused mind would never find.  But who am I?  An outdated tech lead. The way I did it was, I bought a book about coding one language (a physical book, not pdf or so). I settled it in my mind that I will consume this book page by page until I reach the end. Also, I made sure not to go the next page until I understood the current page 100%. When I reached the end of the book, I was REALLY comfortable with this programming language. Additionally, it gave me the necessary basic understanding of programming which allowed me to learn from internet tutoriais and pdfs actually effectively. I didnâ€™t need to fully read another full book to learn a different language from then on. Just that initial book propelled me to a state where I was perfectly comfortable with programming itself so from then on I could learn from little bits here and there and be able to connect the dots. Literally got myself a programming job when I finished the book.

Wow, I completely disagree 100% with everything you're saying. First of all, thank you for sharing your story and your way of learning, but this video should be called "How I learn to code". It takes more than sitting on the computer and focus, and I understand that it worked for you, but that doesn't mean that's the way to learn, it's just your personality and the way you do things, you said it yourself, you like being at home, not going out, which is fine, but staying at home does not make a programmer. The way I see it is that coding, programming, or solving problems related to software development is also a people problem, you might need an opinion, or contribution from someone, and to do that, you need to able to communicate a problem, and that means you have to step outside "the zone" and be able to discuss or engage into a conversation.   Sometimes, inspiration comes from the place you least expected, and sometimes that is not a computer screen. I do agree that in order to learn how to code, well, you have to code, and that involves sitting in front of a computer, possible some hours per day. Having said that, by no means that indicates that events in life must be stopped, but, if that's your personality, go for it, but don't feel that you have to sacrifice a trip to the mall because that would make you a bad programmer.

Best way is ask what you want to do, then explain the steps to get it done. I want to add two numbers?  How many variables make up this question? 3: two variables and a sum; ok write this out.  Ex: x = "X: "; Ect.  Our values are Ints and not strings so lets fix this.  x = ConvertToInt32(x);  How do we get the input for this from user? Console.WriteLine("X: " ); Console.Readline();   Now that we have our two varibles how do we add them?  sum = x + y;  Now how do we relay the answer to the users question?  Console.WriteLine() = sum; Console.ReadLine();  Cool our code works! Can we simplify? Yes! //name new program public additionProgram() { //set variables int x; int y;  //get user to update variables x = Console.WriteLine("X: "); y = Console.WriteLine("Y: ");  //combine users variables Int sum = x + y;  //tell user thier total Console.ReadLine() = sum; }//end program  congrats you have learned the bare bones of learning to properly code with C# or any other programming language. You can look up most code syntax with google, stackoverflow, or documentation no one knows all the syntax just need to ask the right question. If you get an error or a bug its usually implementation such as order of what your trying to do or told it to do something worng.   Computers are dumb as rocks and need to be hand held through each step. If you skip steps such as not declairing a variable or telling it to do something like did you take out the trash but you never asked it in the first place its going to get confused.   All you really need to know is what are the variables, syntax functions/methods are just shortcuts for what you want the variables to do, and classes are just the shopping list you need your rock to go fill from the store.

I loved everything about my degree program, designing interfaces, and building applications. I started tinkering with websites and code in high school (while I gamed a lot too). I've always been fascinated with logic, creativity, puzzles, technology, music, and animation. I grew fond of math and physics in my degree program and learned to love the art of problem solving. That and communication are the two greatest skills you can obtain in my opinion anywhere.

Landing that first job advice (after you've developed some actual programming ability): get your foot into the door of a startup/small tech company by any means necessary.  Meaning, take a low-level or intern position if that's all they can offer, even if it's doing completely menial tasks.  Because trust me, once you get in the door, you are going to play multiple roles and learn very fast, as long as you're willing to take on any role that's needed.  There are always more roles to play/hats to wear than bodies.  Let it be known that you have some programming experience.  Solve small problems for tech leads, freeing them to concentrate on the bigger problems.  You will eventually gain their trust, and they will by necessity/desperation start throwing bigger problems at you.  Solve those.  Win.  You are now a Tech Lead and very marketable.

The part about college degrees not teaching you programming isn't entirely inaccurate. I don't know how computer science programmes work in the US, but in the UK, any decent computer science degree will have comprehensive courses in object-oriented programming. Most will teach Java throughout the first and second year alongside the typical data structures and algorithms type courses. In the first year, they will teach basic syntax, object-oriented features and exception handling, and in the second year they move on to more advanced topics like network programming with sockets and using GUI frameworks. Alongside Java, they may also have shorter courses on other languages, such as functional languages or systems programming in C/C++, and modern courses will also teach basic web front-end development using HTML, CSS and Javascript. Once you know a language like Java, it's not hard to transfer your knowledge to learning other languages like C# or Swift, so they give you a pretty good foundation.

Best and simple  tip : Cut away distractors and time wasters. Go under desk, disconnect LAN cable from PC, physically, switch your phone to quiet mode, put it away 5 meters away from you. Only then you can start learning anything. It is an OFFLINE PC then. Old times. If you are connected to the Internet, your effort and enthusiasm will be wasted. You need to cut yourself away from "quick checks" of fav web sites, instagram, emails and other time wasters. Internet will still be there when you return to it during evening. Nothing will be missed. I  have made something else even. I created a second Windows partition, which has no Internet set in Windows. LAN card disabled. If I switch to that partition I never connect to the Internet to check anything.  I know then If I really, really and really need to start Internet I have to reboot to load "online deskop" Windows partition, with bookmarks and passwords stored, which is a no no. Too much effort.  With your OFFLINE PC Windows, you read PDFs you downloaded previously or video courses. All offline, on your disk. It is like going back to old times when you had dial-up Internet and were disconnected for most of the time. FOCUS is the most important thing, elimination of distractors. Cheers :)

So true, I went to uni thinking I would be taught programming, my degree was computer and network technology heavily based on networking and programming. I was in for a shock they only taught us fundamentals and gave us assignments to create programs etc in Java, I spent hours everyday (6, 7 sometimes over 12 at home by myself) youtube, java book, stack overflow etc, and came out with first class honours. In my final year I created a project 'remote control home automation using IoT' this project I started 3 months early (in summer break) and included languages of (C, pyhton, java, HTML, PHP and sql. I programmed everything from scratch. The project was to control my house heating, water, lighting, cameras and other appliances of the house automatically and remotely via a an Android app or a website. So to program sensors i boguht of eBay (motion sensor, temp sensor, humidity sensor etc..etc I used language C (where all my conditions were outlined i.e. if temp if room falls below 18 degrees and motion in house is being detected etc turn heating on etc and many more , then to send this data across to an a program that filters the data and further logs it to an sql database I used python, then to have this system monitored remotely on a phone I created a java app which not only displayed real time data, but also gave information about electricity consumption and also have the manual remote control, i.e. trun light on button, turn heating off etc, turn kettle on, .... Then the website I created was just the alternative to the phone application. But yes this project took my 8 months and I spent good 12 hours a day some days and many weeks not going out just doing this day everyday and at the end of the project I scored a First (just like all my other projects). Once uni was over I went on holiday the same day my last exam finished, then the day I got back I started applying for jobs, as a technical analyst (not programmer ) and two weeks later after 2 interviews at my first job invite I got the place and negotiated my salsry and here I am still here. So you must be thinking why didn't I go for a programmers job? Well even though I spent many hours learning programming etc, I must have spent 10 times that much time learning networking and cloud etc. I am a globally Cisco certified network engineer (I mentioned in my third year summer I spent alot time on programming doing my final year project. Well in second year  summer I spent for two months constant everyday from 10 hours to 12 hours a day becoming a Cisco certified network engineer the course was so big (that I actually think it was more then my three years of uni work) but I spent 12 hours a day for 2 and half months and it was so bad that even in my dreams no lie I would be thinking about networking etc. Anyway I sat the exam and failed. Which I could not believe as I knew it all like the back of my hand, so I re booked the esrliest exam date and did zero revision till that exam as I had done so much revision that I could literally see my notes book in my mind anyway I sat the exam and passed. Came into third year of uni knowing absolute everything to a point that lecturers would ask me to explain, fix, troubleshoot things in the network labs we had. But yes people think and be jelous of other people's end results yet have no idea about the struggle they went through . What I did for months people would not be able to continue after the third day it was system overload of learning new things  and doing revision daily of everything u have learnt from previous day's. But yes since you don't have the time contraint as I had (I had 2 months only before uni was starting again) you can take it much more easier but most important most most important if you take anything from this is learn how to be SELF MOTIVATED.. don't be like ohh this isn't for me I am not self motivated, well learn how to be it then!  so now u think I am a nerd well let me tell you my other life. I have been doing taekwondo for 12 years I was in the great Britain team representing England for a full year (currently a blackbelt 2nd Dan). So point being whatever you do in life don't touch and go master it become the best or better then you were yesterday then go. But yes it's only been around 9 months since I graduated I am aiming to start my own thing as this work cycle system is system that doesn't let you be independent and honestly I am sick of it..
